In a press briefing, White House Press Secretary Karine Jean-Pierre provided an overview of the administration's response to Hurricane Fiona in Puerto Rico. President Biden issued an emergency disaster declaration before the hurricane made landfall, and FEMA Administrator Deanne Criswell is on the ground to assess the emergency response. Power restoration efforts have begun, and federal responders are on the ground to assist with the recovery. President Biden is receiving regular updates on the situation and has called on the international community to support Puerto Rico. 

The briefing also included remarks from National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan, who discussed President Biden's upcoming participation in the U.N. General Assembly. Sullivan highlighted the President's vision for American foreign policy and principled leadership in the world. He emphasized the importance of strengthening the United Nations and called for continued support for Ukraine in the face of Russian aggression. Sullivan also mentioned the President's meetings with world leaders and the focus on global food security and climate change.

In the Q&A portion of the briefing, topics included the impact of the hurricane on Puerto Rico's ability to hold gains in its counteroffensive, the President's commitment to defending Taiwan in the event of an attack by China, reports of Russia planning sham referenda in Ukraine, and the President's meeting with the families of Brittney Griner and Paul Whelan. Other questions covered Iran, the situation at the U.S.-Mexico border, and the President's remarks on the pandemic being over.